{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17631298","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17631298"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:26:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:26:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17364"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17364","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17364"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10054"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115207"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10054","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10054"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17364"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97215"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"5395"},{"type":"tags","id":"7846"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23543"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23549"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115207","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115207"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA researcher conducts a two-year study comparing two weight loss programs. The study begins with 200 participants in each group. After one year, 150 participants remain in program A while only 80 remain in program B.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following types of bias is most likely to be present in this study?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Attrition bias","Selection bias","Information bias","Recall bias","Performance bias"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario demonstrates \u003Cstrong\u003Eattrition bias\u003C/strong\u003E, which occurs when participants drop out of a study non-randomly. The differential dropout rates (25% vs 60%) suggest systematic differences between the groups, potentially compromising the study\u0027s validity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESelection bias\u003C/strong\u003E refers to systematic differences in how participants are chosen for the study initially, which is not the issue here. \u003Cstrong\u003EInformation bias\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when there are systematic differences in how data is collected between groups. \u003Cstrong\u003ERecall bias\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when there are systematic differences in the accuracy or completeness of participants\u0027 memories about past events. \u003Cstrong\u003EPerformance bias\u003C/strong\u003E refers to systematic differences in the care provided to groups apart from the intervention being studied.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETo address attrition bias, researchers should analyse the characteristics of participants who dropped out, conduct intention-to-treat analysis, and clearly report dropout rates and reasons in their findings.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Attrition bias occurs when participants drop out of a study non-randomly, leading to systematic differences between groups.","Loss to follow-up can significantly affect study validity if the characteristics of those who drop out differ from those who remain.","Attrition bias is particularly problematic in longitudinal studies and clinical trials with extended follow-up periods."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004.","Nunan D, Aronson J, Bankhead C. Catalogue of bias: attrition bias. BMJ Evid Based Med. 2018 Feb;23(1):21-22. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29367321/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97215"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17364"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97215","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97215"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T10:01:55+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T10:01:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10054"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115207"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4948"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udcca","name":"Biostatistics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T13:30:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"typ